---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import FoundationPager from '../../components/FoundationPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'Anti-patterns';
const description =
  'Ten things that look like good context engineering and are not. Reject every one of them, including in your own output.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="foundation">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    Things that look like good context engineering and are not. Reject every
    one of them, including in your own output.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Monolithic prompt bloat</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> A <code>CLAUDE.md</code> or system prompt that
    runs to thousands of words and includes the product roadmap, customer
    personas, architecture diagram, and brand voice guidelines.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> The model has a finite attention budget.
    Burying the actual rules under marketing copy means the rules get ignored.
    Every token of bloat also costs money on every invocation.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> One kind of content per file. Reference docs are
    pulled in on demand via <code>@docs</code> or filepath mentions. The
    Project layer file stays under 200 lines.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Vague principles without examples</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> Rules like "use good judgment", "write clean
    code", "follow our style guide", "maintain high test coverage".
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> "Clean" is a vibe, not a rule. The agent
    has seen every "clean code" book in training and will pick whichever
    interpretation produces the most output. There is no shared definition.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> Every rule is <strong>behaviorally anchored</strong>:
    it names the exact technology, command, or pattern the agent should reach
    for. Anchored beats abstract in every category.
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Category</th><th>Anchored (good)</th><th>Vague (bad)</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Error handling</td>
        <td>Wrap external API calls in try/catch; log failures via <code>Logger</code>; never swallow exceptions.</td>
        <td>"Write robust error handling."</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Styling</td>
        <td>Tailwind utilities only; conditional classes via <code>cn()</code>; assets in <code>/assets/</code>.</td>
        <td>"Use clean styling patterns."</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Testing</td>
        <td>Vitest; assert on user actions; run <code>npm run test:coverage</code> before staging.</td>
        <td>"Maintain high test coverage."</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Git workflow</td>
        <td>Conventional Commits; one-file scope where reasonable; humans sole authors of record.</td>
        <td>"Commit often with helpful messages."</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Dependencies</td>
        <td>Pin critical packages; named imports; <code>npm run build</code> to verify types on modified modules.</td>
        <td>"Keep dependencies updated."</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    Anchored rules carry a verb, a named tool or pattern, and a verification
    path. Vague rules carry an adjective and hope.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Placeholder comments</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> The agent leaves <code>// TODO: implement
    this</code> or <code>pass  # come back later</code> in shipped code.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> TODOs never come back. They become
    permanent. The next agent reading the file thinks "implement this" is a
    real instruction and writes something speculative.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> Every function is either fully implemented or not
    included. If the agent does not have enough context to implement, it
    stops and asks.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Implicit local assumptions</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> Instructions like "use the local Postgres" or
    "open the file in VS Code" without specifying which.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> The agent does not know your timezone, OS,
    shell, Node version, default browser, or scratch directory. It will guess,
    and the guess is statistically wrong.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> State the assumption explicitly in the Session
    layer, or have the agent ask before assuming. Never bake
    personal-environment assumptions into the Project layer.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Over-exposing tools</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> An MCP configuration that exposes every tool
    the agent could possibly need, "just in case".
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> Every tool description costs tokens. Twenty
    tool descriptions means twenty competing things to consider before doing
    anything. The agent picks wrong more often, costs more, and the security
    blast radius is huge.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> Route tools by intent. See
    <a href={url('foundation/mcp-principles/')}>MCP principles</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Rules that fire everywhere</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> A <code>.cursor/rules/global.mdc</code> that
    applies to every file in the repo and contains both frontend and backend
    conventions.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> When the agent edits a React component, it
    does not need SQL migration conventions. They distract.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> Scope rules to file patterns. The
    <a href={url('commands/scope/')}><code>scope</code></a> command exists for
    this.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Stale context</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> A <code>CLAUDE.md</code> that still says "we use
    Yarn 1" three months after the team migrated to pnpm.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> The agent confidently follows the stale
    instructions and produces non-working scripts. The team blames AI when
    the real failure is ContextOps.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> Pre-commit hook that validates context files against
    detected stack. <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a>
    sets this up; <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a>
    catches existing drift.
  </p>

  <h2>8. Treating memory as repo context</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> "Magnus prefers terse responses" written into
    <code>CLAUDE.md</code>.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> That is a fact about Magnus, not about the
    repo. Another engineer joins, reads the file, and the agent now thinks
    they prefer terse responses too. Cross-contamination.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> User preferences live in agent memory or per-user
    config, not in versioned repo files. The Project layer describes the
    <em>project</em>, not the <em>people</em>.
  </p>

  <h2>9. Negative-space silence</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> No record anywhere of approaches the team
    considered and rejected.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> The agent will eventually suggest the
    rejected approach (every time, forever), because it does not know it was
    rejected.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> Capture rejections in ADRs with a "Considered
    alternatives" section, or in a dedicated <code>docs/decisions/negative-space.md</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>10. Verification as an afterthought</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Symptom.</strong> Context files that tell the agent what to do
    but not how to check the result.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why it fails.</strong> The agent has no way to self-correct. The
    human becomes the verification step, which is slow and unreliable.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Fix.</strong> Every instruction that produces an artifact also
    names the command that verifies it. Bake it in with
    <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a>.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Source" tone="mute">
    <p>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#good-practices')}>2026 Context Engineering
      Blueprint: Practices to Avoid</a>. The flipside is
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>good practices</a>.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <FoundationPager slug="anti-patterns" />
</Doc>
